{{Use American English|date=May 2012}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}
'''Experimental political science''' is the use of [[experiment]]s, which may be [[natural experiment|natural]] or [[scientific control|controlled]], to implement the [[scientific method]] in [[political science]].

== History and usage ==
The first experiment in political science is regarded to be Harold Gosnell's 1924 study on voter turnout in Chicago.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Morton|first1=Rebecca B.|last2=Williams|first2=Kenneth C.|title=Experimentation in Political Science|journal=The Oxford Handbook of Political Methodology|url=http://www.nyu.edu/gsas/dept/politics/faculty/morton/ExpChapHandbook5April06.pdf|accessdate=26 July 2014}}</ref> In this experiment, he randomly assigned districts to receive information on voter registration and encouragements to vote.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gosnell|first1=Harold F.|title=An Experiment in the Stimulation of Voting|journal=American Political Science Review|date=1926|volume=20|issue=4|pages=869–874|url=http://www.ib.ethz.ch/teaching/pwgrundlagen/Gosnell-Experiment-Voting-1926.pdf|accessdate=26 July 2014|doi=10.2307/1945435}}</ref> Current experts in experimental methodology in political science include [[Rebecca Morton]] and [[Donald Green]]. 

Since then, experimental research has become a growing area of political science. The publication of experimental research articles in flagship political science journals has risen, especially since the 1980s. Moreover, [[citation analysis]] indicates that articles using experimental methods have higher rates of citation.

Among the areas that it is used in are:
* [[Political psychology]], including [[survey methodology]], [[loss aversion]], influences on [[voter turnout]], and [[media influence]];
* The effects on outcomes of different [[voting systems]] (''e.g.'', [[Storable Votes#Experimental Results|storable votes]]), including the study of [[tactical voting]]; 
* The political economy of development;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Humphreys|first1=Macartan |last2=Weinstein | first2 = Jeremy  |title=Field experiments and the Political Economy of Development|journal = Annual Review of Political Science |date=2009|volume=12|pages=367–378|url=http://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev.polisci.12.060107.155922|accessdate=13 August 2014 |doi=10.1146/annurev.polisci.12.060107.155922}}</ref> 
* International relations<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hyde|first1=Susan D. |title=The future of field experiments in International Relations|journal = The Annals of the American Academy of Political and Social Science |date=2010|volume=628|issue=1|pages=72–84|url=http://ann.sagepub.com/content/628/1/72.short|accessdate=13 August 2014|doi=10.1177/0002716209351513}}</ref> 

* Interactions and voting in [[legislatures]] (and other [[deliberative assembly|deliberative assemblies]]), including the effects of different [[voting methods in deliberative assemblies|voting methods]] and control of the [[agenda (meeting)|agenda]].<ref name=liberalism_populism>{{cite book|title=Liberalism Against Populism|first=William|last=Riker|authorlink=William H. Riker|isbn=0-88133-367-0|year=1988|origyear=First published in 1982|publisher=Waveland Press|location=Prospect Heights, Illinois, USA}}</ref>

